I find it so ever interesting that so many years cna pass and we all still hold our blinders close to our eyes.  Our country is really one of the best anywhere in the world specifically because of our right and ability to speak freely.  But our government has tried to suppress these rights - and the Anti-Vietnam War Protest movement was no exception.  <br><br>
I served in Vietnam AND I was against the war.  I had many friends in the 'Nam, both lifers and draftees.  But with few exceptions, we all shared a common feeling:  we were there against their wills and we all wanted to go home alive.  I personally knew GI's who went go-over-the-hill on R&amp;R and never returned to duty just to get out alive.  <br><br>
Fact:  War kills, period.  What really pisses me off is that there is never any dialog about the tens of thousands of Vietnamese, Laotian, and Cambodian civilains that died there, many at the hands of American GIs.  <br><br>
Maybe Jane Fonda was wrong, I don't know.  I was in-country when she did it.  But I know that while were in 'Nam, the only way we could find out what was going on back home was through letters from our friends in &quot;the world&quot; and we were technically prohibited from sending pictures back home of the atrocities that we witnessed there.  <br><br>
And when I came home, I did get spit upon, and I was against the war!!  There is no excuse for the treatment of those who served against their wills and lived to return to hostile receptions.  Had we all refused to go, there would have been no war - but that didn't happen. <br><br>
But we must learn to forgive each other.  If Joel Hunt reads this, I hope he can remember that there wasn't any glory in what we did over there, it was slaughter or get slaughtered.<br>
Do you remember the in-country name for the military's &quot;Search-and-Destroy&quot; missions?  (&quot;Search-and-Avoid&quot;)<br><br>
Our missio was just to stay alive so that we could come home.<br><br>

